:INFO
Common Natto Problems
Most natto failures trace back to temperature and contamination. This page covers the most common issues and how to diagnose them.

:PATH
No Strings After 24 Hours
Temperature likely dropped below 95 F — fermentation stalled.
|
:INFO
No Strings After 24 Hours
If beans look wet but pull no strings, the culture stalled. Check your thermometer — did temperature drop overnight? You can try extending fermentation another 4 to 6 hours at proper temp. If no strings appear by hour 30, the batch has likely failed. Causes: cold snap, starter too old, or beans were too cool when inoculated.

:PATH
Strong Ammonia Smell
Normal in small amounts — overwhelming smell means over-fermented.
|
:INFO
Strong Ammonia Smell
Some ammonia is normal and mellows after 24 hours in the fridge. An overwhelming ammonia smell after refrigeration means fermentation ran too long or too hot. The natto is still safe to eat but flavor is very pungent. Next batch: reduce fermentation time by 2 hours or lower temp by 2 to 3 degrees.

:PATH
Pink or Black Spots on Beans
Contamination — discard this batch immediately.
|
:INFO
Pink or Black Spots on Beans
Any pink, red, orange, or black coloration on the beans indicates bacterial or mold contamination. This is not Bacillus subtilis. Discard the entire batch. Sterilize all equipment with boiling water before the next attempt. Contamination usually enters through inadequately cleaned tools or insufficiently cooked beans.

:PATH
Beans Are Dry and Hard After Fermentation
Surface dried out — humidity was too low during ferment.
|
:INFO
Beans Are Dry and Hard After Fermentation
Natto needs some humidity to ferment properly. If your chamber was too dry, place a small dish of water inside alongside the trays. Cover trays with foil that has a few small holes poked in it rather than open mesh. Dry beans ferment unevenly and the starter cannot spread effectively.

:NOTE
Starter Potency Degrades Over Time
Natto starter spores lose viability if stored improperly. Keep unused starter in an airtight container in the freezer. If your last three batches all produced weak results with good temperature control, order fresh starter. Spores stored in the fridge rather than the freezer can fail within a few months.

:QUOTE
Natto troubleshooting is temperature troubleshooting. Fix that first.
